Pneumonia X-Ray Images¶

Adapted version of Paul Mooney's 'Chest X-Ray Images (Pneumonia)' dataset, where the amount of observations for training and validation purposes was redistributed to allow for a more balanced machine learning exercise.

  • Total number of observations (images): 5,856
  • Training observations: 4,192 (1,082 normal cases, 3,110 lung opacity cases)
  • Validation observations: 1,040 (267 normal cases, 773 lung opacity cases)
  • Testing observations: 624 (234 normal cases, 390 lung opacity cases)

Creating a DataFrame

In [2]:
def create_data(normal_path, pneumonia_path):
    data = []
    for filename in os.listdir(normal_path):
        data.append((os.path.join(normal_path, filename), 0))
    for filename in os.listdir(pneumonia_path):
        data.append((os.path.join(pneumonia_path, filename), 1))
    data_df = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=['image_path', 'label'])
    return data_df.sample(frac=1).reset_index(drop=True)

train_data = create_data("C:/Users/Soundarya/Desktop/chestxray/train/normal", "C:/Users/Soundarya/Desktop/chestxray/train/opacity")
val_data = create_data("C:/Users/Soundarya/Desktop/chestxray/test/normal", "C:/Users/Soundarya/Desktop/chestxray/test/opacity")
test_data = create_data("C:/Users/Soundarya/Desktop/chestxray/val/normal", "C:/Users/Soundarya/Desktop/chestxray/val/opacity")

print("Train Data {}".format(train_data.shape))
print("Validation Data {}".format(val_data.shape))
print("Test Data {}".format(test_data.shape))

def vis(images):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
    for i,path in enumerate(images):
        fig.add_subplot(2, 2, i+1)
        img = mimg.imread(path)
        plt.imshow(img,cmap="gist_heat")
        plt.title(train_data[train_data.image_path == path].name.values[0])

for i in range(2):
    images = train_data[train_data.label == i].image_path
    images = np.random.choice(images , 2)
    vis(images)

from tensorflow.keras.utils import to_categorical

def process_data(data):
    lb = to_categorical(data.label, dtype=int)
    data = data.reset_index().drop(labels='index', axis=1)
    y_labels = pd.DataFrame(lb).add_prefix('label_')
    return pd.concat([data, y_labels], axis=1)

train_data = process_data(train_data)
val_data = process_data(val_data)

print("Training set has {} samples".format(train_data.shape[0]))
print("Validation set has {} samples".format(val_data.shape[0]))

Training set has 4192 samples
Validation set has 624 samples
In [11]:
BATCH_SIZE = 32
IMG_SHAPE = 224
EPOCHS = 20

def create_gen(data, image_gen_args):
    image_gen = ImageDataGenerator(**image_gen_args)
    return image_gen.flow_from_dataframe(data,
                                         x_col='image_path',
                                         y_col=[f'label_{x}' for x in np.arange(2)],
                                         class_mode='raw',
                                         batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
                                         target_size=(IMG_SHAPE, IMG_SHAPE))

def gen():
    train_gen_args = {'rescale': 1./255,
                      'width_shift_range': 0.1,
                      'height_shift_range': 0.1,
                      'brightness_range': [0.2, 1.0],
                      'zoom_range': 0.2,
                      'horizontal_flip': True,
                      'vertical_flip': True,
                      'fill_mode': 'nearest'}

    val_gen_args = {'rescale': 1./255}

    train_gen = create_gen(train_data, train_gen_args)
    val_gen = create_gen(val_data, val_gen_args)

    return train_gen, val_gen

class_weights = dict(enumerate(class_weights))

Model Building

VGG-16

VGG16 is a convolutional neural network architecture named after the Visual Geometry Group from Oxford, who developed it. It was used to win the ILSVRC (ImageNet) competition in 2014.

  • Input Layer: Takes an input image of a fixed size (224 x 224 x 3).
  • Convolutional Layers: Contains 16 weight layers - 13 convolutional layers and 3 fully connected layers.
  • Convolutional Blocks: Organized into five blocks, each containing two or three convolutional layers followed by a max-pooling layer.
  • Fully Connected Layers: Three fully connected layers of 4096, 4096, and 1000 nodes, respectively. The final layer has a softmax activation function, outputting 1000 probabilities corresponding to the 1000 ImageNet classes.
  • Activation Function: ReLU (Rectified Linear Activation) is used after each convolution operation.
  • Total Parameters: Around 138 million parameters.
In [13]:
from tensorflow.keras.applications.vgg16 import VGG16

base = VGG16(weights = 'imagenet', include_top = False, input_shape = (224, 224, 3))
tf.keras.backend.clear_session()

for layer in base.layers:
    layer.trainable = False
    
vgg_model = Sequential()
vgg_model.add(base)
vgg_model.add(GlobalAveragePooling2D())
vgg_model.add(BatchNormalization())
vgg_model.add(Dense(256, activation='relu'))
vgg_model.add(Dropout(0.5))
vgg_model.add(BatchNormalization())
vgg_model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
vgg_model.add(Dropout(0.5))
vgg_model.add(Dense(2, activation='softmax'))

vgg_model.summary()

from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping
train_gen, val_gen = gen()

optm = Adam(lr=0.0001)
vgg_model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=optm, 
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

EarlyStopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss',
                              min_delta=.0001,
                              patience=3,
                              verbose=1,
                              mode='auto',
                              baseline=None,
                              restore_best_weights=True)

model_save = ModelCheckpoint('./vgg16_model.h5',
                             save_best_only = True,
                             save_weights_only = False,
                             monitor = 'val_loss', 
                             mode = 'min', verbose = 1)


vgg_history = vgg_model.fit(train_gen,
                             steps_per_epoch = train_gen.samples // BATCH_SIZE,
                             epochs = 10,
                             validation_data = val_gen,
                             callbacks=[EarlyStopping, model_save],
                             class_weight = class_weights)

In [15]:
def plot(history):
    epochs_range = range(len(history.history['accuracy']))
    metrics = [('accuracy', 'Training and Validation Accuracy'), ('loss', 'Training and Validation Loss')]

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))

    for i, (metric, title) in enumerate(metrics, 1):
        plt.subplot(1, 2, i)
        plt.plot(epochs_range, history.history[metric], label=f'Training {metric.capitalize()}')
        plt.plot(epochs_range, history.history[f'val_{metric}'], label=f'Validation {metric.capitalize()}')
        plt.legend(loc='lower right' if metric == 'accuracy' else 'upper right')
        plt.title(title)

    plt.show()

In [18]:
from PIL import Image
def predict(image_path, model):
    im = cv2.imread(image_path)
    test_image = np.asarray(im)
    processed_test_image = process_image(test_image)
    processed_test_image = np.expand_dims(processed_test_image, axis = 0)
    
    ps = model.predict(processed_test_image);
    return ps
    
def process_image(image):
    image = tf.cast(image , tf.float32)
    image = tf.image.resize(image , (224 , 224))
    image = image/255
    image = image.numpy()
    return image
In [19]:
vgg_pred =[]
for image in test_data.image_path:
    vgg_pred.append(predict(image , vgg_model))
    
final_vgg_pred  = np.argmax(vgg_pred , axis=-1)
actual_label = test_data['label']

print(classification_report(actual_label, final_vgg_pred))
matrix=confusion_matrix(actual_label, final_vgg_pred)
sns.heatmap(matrix,square=True, annot=True, fmt='d', cbar=False,
            xticklabels=['0', '1'],
            yticklabels=['0', '1'])
plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
plt.ylabel('True label');

In [ ]:

DenseNet169

DenseNet169 (Densely Connected Convolutional Networks)

  • Input Layer: Typically takes an input image of size (224 x 224 x 3).
  • Dense Blocks: Contains several densely connected blocks. Each layer within these blocks receives the feature-maps of all preceding layers, concatenating them channel-wise.
  • Growth Rate: A hyperparameter that defines the number of output feature-maps of each internal layer. It controls how much new information each layer contributes to the global state.
  • Bottleneck Layers: Used to reduce the input dimensionality before expensive convolution operations, thus improving computational efficiency.
  • Transition Layers: Between dense blocks, where the feature-maps are concatenated, followed by a batch normalization layer and a 1x1 convolution layer, and then downsampled using 2x2 average pooling.
  • Final Fully Connected Layer: The final classification layer typically has a softmax activation function, and the number of nodes corresponds to the number of classes.
  • Total Parameters: Around 14 million parameters for DenseNet169.
In [20]:
 from tensorflow.keras.applications import DenseNet169
from tensorflow.keras.layers import GlobalAveragePooling2D, Dense, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model

base = DenseNet169(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(224, 224, 3))
base.trainable = False

x = GlobalAveragePooling2D()(base.output)
x = Dense(256, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
output = Dense(2, activation='softmax')(x)

densenet_model = Model(inputs=base.input, outputs=output)
densenet_model.summary()

from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping

train_gen, val_gen = gen()

optm = Adam(lr=0.0001)
densenet_model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=optm, 
                       metrics=['accuracy'])

early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss',
                               min_delta=0.0001,
                               patience=3,
                               verbose=1,
                               mode='auto',
                               restore_best_weights=True)

dense_history = densenet_model.fit(train_gen,
                                   steps_per_epoch=train_gen.samples // BATCH_SIZE,
                                   epochs=5,
                                   validation_data=val_gen,
                                   callbacks=[early_stopping])

dense_pred =[]
for image in test_data.image_path:#using test data
    dense_pred.append(predict(image , densenet_model));
    
final_dense_pred  = np.argmax(dense_pred , axis=-1);
actual_label = test_data['label']

print(classification_report(actual_label, final_dense_pred))
matrix=confusion_matrix(actual_label, final_dense_pred)
sns.heatmap(matrix,square=True, annot=True, fmt='d', cbar=False,
            xticklabels=['0', '1'],
            yticklabels=['0', '1'])
plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
plt.ylabel('True label');

In [24]:
def compare_histories(vgg_history, dense_history):
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 6))

    # Plot Training Accuracy
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(vgg_history.history['accuracy'], label='VGG16 Training Accuracy')
    plt.plot(dense_history.history['accuracy'], label='DenseNet Training Accuracy')
    plt.plot(vgg_history.history['val_accuracy'], label='VGG16 Validation Accuracy')
    plt.plot(dense_history.history['val_accuracy'], label='DenseNet Validation Accuracy')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy Comparison')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.legend()

    # Plot Training Loss
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(vgg_history.history['loss'], label='VGG16 Training Loss')
    plt.plot(dense_history.history['loss'], label='DenseNet Training Loss')
    plt.plot(vgg_history.history['val_loss'], label='VGG16 Validation Loss')
    plt.plot(dense_history.history['val_loss'], label='DenseNet Validation Loss')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Loss Comparison')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()

    plt.show()
In [25]:
# Call the function with the history objects
compare_histories(vgg_history, dense_history)

Training Accuracy: Both models show a similar trend in training accuracy, with DenseNet having a slightly higher accuracy than VGG16. The training accuracy is increasing for both models, which is a positive sign.

Validation Accuracy: Again, DenseNet shows a slightly higher validation accuracy than VGG16. The validation accuracy is also increasing, though it is less smooth compared to the training accuracy.

Training Loss: Both models show a decreasing trend in training loss, with DenseNet having a slightly lower loss compared to VGG16. This is consistent with the increase in training accuracy.

Validation Loss: The validation loss is decreasing for both models but seems to have more fluctuations. DenseNet shows a lower validation loss compared to VGG16.

Overfitting: In this case, both training and validation losses are decreasing, so there's no clear evidence of overfitting at this stage.

Model Performance: From this plot, DenseNet seems to be performing slightly better than VGG16 in terms of both accuracy and loss on the given dataset.

VGG-19

-Input Layer: Takes an input image of a fixed size (224 x 224 x 3).

-Convolutional Layers: Contains 19 weight layers - 16 convolutional layers and 3 fully connected layers.

-Convolutional Blocks: Organized into five blocks, each containing two or three convolutional layers followed by a max-pooling layer.

-Fully Connected Layers: Three fully connected layers of 4096, 4096, and 1000 nodes, respectively. The final layer has a softmax activation function, outputting 1000 probabilities corresponding to the 1000 ImageNet classes.

-Activation Function: ReLU (Rectified Linear Activation) is used after each convolution operation.

-Total Parameters: Around 143.7 million parameters. VGG19 is a slightly deeper version of VGG16 with an extra convolutional layer in each block. It also has more parameters due to its deeper architecture.

In [26]:
from tensorflow.keras.applications.vgg19 import VGG19
base_model = VGG19(weights = 'imagenet', include_top = False, input_shape = (224, 224, 3))
tf.keras.backend.clear_session()

for layer in base.layers:
    layer.trainable = False
    
vgg_model1 = Sequential()
vgg_model1.add(base)
vgg_model1.add(GlobalAveragePooling2D())
vgg_model1.add(BatchNormalization())
vgg_model1.add(Dense(256, activation='relu'))
vgg_model1.add(Dropout(0.5))
vgg_model1.add(BatchNormalization())
vgg_model1.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
vgg_model1.add(Dropout(0.5))
vgg_model1.add(Dense(2, activation='softmax'))

vgg_model1.summary()

                  metrics=['accuracy'])

                              min_delta=.0001,

                              restore_best_weights=True)

                             save_best_only = True,
                             save_weights_only = False,
                             monitor = 'val_loss', 
                             mode = 'min', verbose = 1)

                             steps_per_epoch = train_gen.samples // BATCH_SIZE,
                             epochs = 10,
                             validation_data = val_gen,
                             callbacks=[EarlyStopping, model_save],
                             class_weight = class_weights)

In [30]:
from PIL import Image
def predict(image_path, model):
    im = cv2.imread(image_path)
    test_image = np.asarray(im)
    processed_test_image = process_image(test_image)
    processed_test_image = np.expand_dims(processed_test_image, axis = 0)
    
    ps = model.predict(processed_test_image);
    return ps
    
def process_image(image):
    image = tf.cast(image , tf.float32)
    image = tf.image.resize(image , (224 , 224))
    image = image/255
    image = image.numpy()
    return image

from tensorflow.keras.applications import InceptionV3
base = InceptionV3(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(224, 224, 3))


for layer in base.layers:
    layer.trainable = False


x = GlobalAveragePooling2D()(base.output)
x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
output = Dense(2, activation='softmax')(x)


incep_model = Model(inputs=base.input, outputs=output)


incep_model.summary()

from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping

train_gen, val_gen = gen()

optm = Adam(lr=0.0001)
incep_model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=optm, 
                       metrics=['accuracy'])

early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss',
                               min_delta=0.0001,
                               patience=3,
                               verbose=1,
                               mode='auto',
                               restore_best_weights=True)
model_save = ModelCheckpoint('./incep.h5',
                             save_best_only = True,
                             save_weights_only = False,
                             monitor = 'val_loss', 
                             mode = 'min', verbose = 1)

incep_history = incep_model.fit(train_gen,
                                   steps_per_epoch=train_gen.samples // BATCH_SIZE,
                                   epochs=10,
                                   validation_data=val_gen,
                                   callbacks=[early_stopping])

In [36]:
incep_pred =[]
for image in test_data.image_path:#using test data
    incep_pred.append(predict(image , incep_model));
    
final_incep_pred  = np.argmax(incep_pred , axis=-1);
actual_label = test_data['label']

print(classification_report(actual_label, final_incep_pred))
matrix=confusion_matrix(actual_label, final_incep_pred)
sns.heatmap(matrix,square=True, annot=True, fmt='d', cbar=False,
            xticklabels=['0', '1'],
            yticklabels=['0', '1'])
plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
plt.ylabel('True label');

In [37]:
def compare_histories(vgg_history, dense_history):
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 6))

    # Plot Training Accuracy
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(vgg_history1.history['accuracy'], label='VGG19 Training Accuracy')
    plt.plot(dense_history.history['accuracy'], label='DenseNet Training Accuracy')
    plt.plot(vgg_history1.history['val_accuracy'], label='VGG19 Validation Accuracy')
    plt.plot(dense_history.history['val_accuracy'], label='DenseNet Validation Accuracy')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy Comparison')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.legend()

    # Plot Training Loss
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(vgg_history1.history['loss'], label='VGG19 Training Loss')
    plt.plot(dense_history.history['loss'], label='DenseNet Training Loss')
    plt.plot(vgg_history1.history['val_loss'], label='VGG19 Validation Loss')
    plt.plot(dense_history.history['val_loss'], label='DenseNet Validation Loss')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Loss Comparison')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()

    plt.show()
In [38]:
compare_histories(vgg_history1,dense_history)

def compare_histories(vgg_history, incep_history):
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 6))

    # Plot Training Accuracy
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(vgg_history1.history['accuracy'], label='VGG19 Training Accuracy')
    plt.plot(incep_history.history['accuracy'], label='InceptionV3 Training Accuracy')
    plt.plot(vgg_history1.history['val_accuracy'], label='VGG19 Validation Accuracy')
    plt.plot(incep_history.history['val_accuracy'], label='InceptionV3 Validation Accuracy')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy Comparison')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.legend()

    # Plot Training Loss
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(vgg_history1.history['loss'], label='VGG19 Training Loss')
    plt.plot(incep_history.history['loss'], label='Inceptionv3 Training Loss')
    plt.plot(vgg_history1.history['val_loss'], label='VGG19 Validation Loss')
    plt.plot(incep_history.history['val_loss'], label='InceptionV3 Validation Loss')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Loss Comparison')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()

    plt.show()
compare_histories(vgg_history1,incep_history)

from tensorflow.keras.applications.xception import Xception
base = Xception(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(224, 224, 3))


for layer in base.layers:
    layer.trainable = False


x = GlobalAveragePooling2D()(base.output)
x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
output = Dense(2, activation='softmax')(x)


xcep_model = Model(inputs=base.input, outputs=output)


xcep_model.summary()

from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping

train_gen, val_gen = gen()

optm = Adam(lr=0.0001)
xcep_model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=optm, 
                       metrics=['accuracy'])

early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss',
                               min_delta=0.0001,
                               patience=3,
                               verbose=1,
                               mode='auto',
                               restore_best_weights=True)
model_save = ModelCheckpoint('./xcep.h5',
                             save_best_only = True,
                             save_weights_only = False,
                             monitor = 'val_loss', 
                             mode = 'min', verbose = 1)

xcep_history = xcep_model.fit(train_gen,
                                   steps_per_epoch=train_gen.samples // BATCH_SIZE,
                                   epochs=10,
                                   validation_data=val_gen,
                                   callbacks=[early_stopping])

xcep_pred =[]
for image in test_data.image_path:#using test data
    xcep_pred.append(predict(image , xcep_model));
    
final_xcep_pred  = np.argmax(xcep_pred , axis=-1);
actual_label = test_data['label']

print(classification_report(actual_label, final_xcep_pred))
matrix=confusion_matrix(actual_label, final_xcep_pred)
sns.heatmap(matrix,square=True, annot=True, fmt='d', cbar=False,
            xticklabels=['0', '1'],
            yticklabels=['0', '1'])
plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
plt.ylabel('True label');

def compare_histories(xcep_history, incep_history):
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 6))

    # Plot Training Accuracy
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(xcep_history.history['accuracy'], label='Xception Training Accuracy')
    plt.plot(incep_history.history['accuracy'], label='InceptionV3 Training Accuracy')
    plt.plot(xcep_history.history['val_accuracy'], label='Xception Validation Accuracy')
    plt.plot(incep_history.history['val_accuracy'], label='InceptionV3 Validation Accuracy')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy Comparison')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.legend()

    # Plot Training Loss
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(xcep_history.history['loss'], label='Xception Training Loss')
    plt.plot(incep_history.history['loss'], label='Inceptionv3 Training Loss')
    plt.plot(xcep_history.history['val_loss'], label='Xception Validation Loss')
    plt.plot(incep_history.history['val_loss'], label='InceptionV3 Validation Loss')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Loss Comparison')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()

    plt.show()
compare_histories(xcep_history,incep_history)

Summary

Both VGG16 and DenseNet169 have been used extensively in various computer vision tasks, such as object detection, image segmentation, and classification. While VGG16 is simpler and more straightforward, DenseNet's dense connections make it more parameter-efficient and enable it to capture more complex patterns.
